          <section id="standards-reference">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-5">4. Standards and protocol reference</h2>
            <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
              Every RFID purchase quietly commits a project to a specific ISO or industry standard. The reader fleet, the chip and the workflow software must all speak the same protocol, and no amount of unit-price negotiation can paper over a standard mismatch downstream. Use this table to confirm the standard before requesting samples.
            </p>
            <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-3xl border border-gray-200">
              <table class="w-full text-sm bg-white">
                <thead class="bg-gray-100 text-gray-700">
                  <tr>
                    <th class="px-5 py-4 text-left font-semibold border-b border-gray-200">Standard</th>
                    <th class="px-5 py-4 text-left font-semibold border-b border-gray-200">Scope</th>
                    <th class="px-5 py-4 text-left font-semibold border-b border-gray-200">Notes</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  {standardsReference.map((row, index) => (
                    <tr class={index % 2 === 0 ? 'bg-white' : 'bg-gray-50'}>
                      <td class="px-5 py-4 border-b border-gray-100 text-gray-800 font-semibold align-top">{row.standard}</td>
                      <td class="px-5 py-4 border-b border-gray-100 text-gray-600 align-top">{row.scope}</td>
                      <td class="px-5 py-4 border-b border-gray-100 text-gray-600 align-top">{row.notes}</td>
                    </tr>
                  ))}
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-4 italic">Sources: ISO/IEC, GS1, NFC Forum, RAIN Alliance public specifications (2024).</p>
          </section>

          <section id="regional-compliance">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-5">5. Regional UHF compliance map</h2>
            <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
              UHF RFID is regulated differently in every market. A US-tuned tag at 902-928 MHz will deliver dramatically reduced range in the European 865-868 MHz band, and exporting an unapproved reader can stop a shipment at customs. Specify the target market sub-band before tag tooling.
            </p>
            <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-3xl border border-gray-200">
              <table class="w-full text-sm bg-white">
                <thead class="bg-gray-100 text-gray-700">
                  <tr>
                    <th class="px-5 py-4 text-left font-semibold border-b border-gray-200">Region</th>
                    <th class="px-5 py-4 text-left font-semibold border-b border-gray-200">UHF sub-band</th>
                    <th class="px-5 py-4 text-left font-semibold border-b border-gray-200">Power limit</th>
                    <th class="px-5 py-4 text-left font-semibold border-b border-gray-200">Authority / standard</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
                  {regionalCompliance.map((row, index) => (
                    <tr class={index % 2 === 0 ? 'bg-white' : 'bg-gray-50'}>
                      {row.map((cell, cellIdx) => (
                        <td class={`px-5 py-4 border-b border-gray-100 align-top ${cellIdx === 0 ? 'text-gray-800 font-semibold' : 'text-gray-600'}`}>{cell}</td>
                      ))}
                    </tr>
                  ))}
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-4 italic">Sources: FCC Part 15, ETSI EN 302 208, ARIB STD-T107, GB/T 29768, ANATEL Resolution 506, WPC India Notification (2008-S.O.1763(E)). Power limits expressed at the antenna; system EIRP/ERP varies with antenna gain.</p>
          </section>

          <section id="form-factors">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-5">6. Choosing between cards, tags, labels and wristbands</h2>
            <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
              The best RFID product format depends on how the user or object interacts with the system. The same HF chip could work inside a card, a wristband or a sticker, but each one serves a different operational experience.
            </p>
